---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import FlbChart from '../components/FlbChart.astro';
import DecompBar from '../components/DecompBar.astro';
import LawChart from '../components/LawChart.astro';
import PanelChart from '../components/PanelChart.astro';
import Timeline from '../components/Timeline.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import data from '../data/findings.json';
const h = data.headline;
const m = data.moments;
const col = data.collapse;
const pr = data.premium;
const cp = data.cpt;
---
<Base>
  <Nav />
  <Hero />

  <!-- THE FINDING -->
  <section id="finding">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 · The finding</div>
        <h2>Skewness is the favourite–longshot bias, made literal.</h2>
        <p class="lede">A unit bet on the favourite pays <span class="mono">o−1</span> on a win and
          <span class="mono">−1</span> on a loss — a re-scaled Bernoulli whose skewness depends only on the
          win probability <span class="mono">p</span>. Aggregate it and the market's asymmetry falls out
          mechanically.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split">
        <div class="reveal"><FlbChart /></div>
        <div class="reveal prose">
          <h3>Ex-ante meets ex-post on the identity</h3>
          <p>The de-vigged (implied) skewness reproduces the realised one — globally
            <strong>+{h.skew_ex_ante}</strong> versus <strong>+{h.skew_ex_post}</strong> — and both sit on the
            theoretical curve <span class="mono">(1−2p)/√(p(1−p))</span> across every probability bucket.</p>
          <p>Decomposing the pooled third moment settles where it comes from:</p>
          <DecompBar />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- THE LAW -->
  <section id="law" style="background:var(--surface-2)">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 · The law</div>
        <h2>A league's asymmetry is fixed by its competitiveness — and we prove it without odds.</h2>
        <p class="lede">Measuring competitiveness from the same odds would be circular. So we built it from
          <strong>results only</strong> — a chronological Elo — and from <strong>final standings</strong>.
          The law survives both.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split">
        <div class="reveal prose">
          <h3>Odds only read the sport</h3>
          <p>Odds-implied and results-based favourite strength agree across leagues at
            <strong>r = +{h.corr_elo_odds}</strong>: the market transcribes the competitive structure, it
            doesn't create it. Skewness then tracks the odds-free measures —
            <strong>+{h.corr_skew_upset}</strong> against the Elo upset rate,
            <strong>{h.corr_skew_nollscully}</strong> against the Noll-Scully imbalance ratio.</p>
          <p>And the relationship is not just fitted — it is <strong>derived</strong>. An ordered-probit
            strength model predicts each league's third moment from its first at
            <strong>r = +{h.model_r}</strong> (RMSE {h.model_rmse}). The leagues fall on the theoretical curve.</p>
          <p class="ladder mono">
            odds (circular) −0.90 → Elo (match-level) +0.83 → standings (season) −0.48…−0.63
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal"><LawChart /></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- INVARIANCE -->
  <section id="invariance">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 · Invariance</div>
        <h2>Two decades, no drift.</h2>
        <p class="lede">Because competitiveness is a slow-moving property of the sport, the skewness it pins
          down is a temporal invariant — stable within the modern competitive regime our window spans.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split">
        <div class="reveal"><PanelChart /></div>
        <div class="reveal prose">
          <h3>A structural constant, not a process</h3>
          <p>League fixed effects plus a year term give a trend of <strong>β = +{h.trend_beta}/yr</strong>
            (p = {h.trend_p}); <strong>{Math.round(h.icc*100)}%</strong> of all variance is <em>between</em>
            leagues, not over time. A conservative break search finds a single break across 38 leagues —
            COVID-19 — with no common year.</p>
          <p>The empty-stadium seasons are a natural experiment: home advantage collapsed, the model predicts
            skewness should rise, and it did. The one exogenous shock in twenty years moved the invariant in
            the predicted direction.</p>
          <div class="mini-stats">
            <div><span class="stat-num">1.067→1.009</span><label>overround collapses; skewness barely moves (margin is orthogonal)</label></div>
            <div><span class="stat-num">99.6%</span><label>within-match in the over/under-2.5 binary market too</label></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- SHAPE INVARIANCE -->
  <section id="shape" style="background:var(--surface-2)">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">04 · Shape</div>
        <h2>Not just the third moment — the whole shape.</h2>
        <p class="lede">The mechanical identity generalises to every order. Once competitiveness is held fixed,
          the entire implied distribution — variance, skewness, kurtosis — is one function of the sport, and it
          collapses across leagues.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split">
        <div class="reveal prose">
          <h3>Every moment is mechanical</h3>
          <p>The within-match (intra-game) fraction is <strong>≈ 1 at every order</strong>, from the variance to
            the sixth moment — the whole shape is the algebraic image of the win-probability distribution, not a
            product of pooling. The ordered-probit strength model predicts each league's
            <strong>variance (r = +{m.model_r.var.toFixed(2)})</strong>,
            <strong>skewness (r = +{m.model_r.skew.toFixed(2)})</strong> and
            <strong>excess kurtosis (r = +{m.model_r.exkurt.toFixed(2)})</strong> from its mean favourite
            probability alone.</p>
          <h3>The distribution collapses</h3>
          <p>Standardised returns genuinely differ across leagues (median KS statistic
            <strong>{col.uncond_ks.toFixed(2)}</strong>) — skewness varies with the league. But comparing leagues
            <em>within</em> a band of competitiveness, the median statistic falls to
            <strong>{col.cond_ks.toFixed(2)}</strong>, a <strong>{Math.round(col.drop*100)}% drop</strong>. Hold
            competitiveness fixed and league identity adds essentially nothing.</p>
          <div class="mini-stats">
            <div><span class="stat-num">≈1</span><label>within-match fraction at every order (moments 2–6): the whole shape is mechanical</label></div>
            <div><span class="stat-num">{m.global.exkurt.toFixed(2)}</span><label>global excess kurtosis — the short-tailed signature of a mixture of Bernoullis</label></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal">
          <img src="/f7_collapse.png" alt="Standardised favourite-return ECDFs differ across leagues but collapse within a fixed band of competitiveness"
            style="width:100%;border-radius:12px;border:1px solid var(--line)" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- PRICING / PREFERENCE -->
  <section id="pricing">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 · Pricing</div>
        <h2>Priced by the bias, not beyond it.</h2>
        <p class="lede">If asymmetry is structural, is it <em>priced</em>? Only through the mechanical longshot
          bias — there is no extra league-level premium — and the preference behind that bias is itself a
          stable constant.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="split">
        <div class="reveal prose">
          <h3>No premium beyond the mechanical bias</h3>
          <p>The favourite's −{Math.abs(pr.global.ret*100).toFixed(1)}% return splits exactly into
            <strong>{(pr.global.vig*100).toFixed(1)}% margin</strong> and
            <strong>+{(pr.global.flb*100).toFixed(2)}% longshot bias</strong> — the loss is almost all the
            bookmaker's vig. Stripping the mechanical FLB level, the league residual is
            <strong>uncorrelated with skewness</strong> (r = +{pr.resid_skew_r.toFixed(2)}). Bookmakers leave no
            extra, skewness-linked edge: the asymmetry analogue of margin orthogonality.</p>
          <h3>An invariant preference</h3>
          <p>The bias is the inverse-S probability weighting of prospect theory — fitting Tversky–Kahneman gives
            <strong>γ = {cp.gamma.toFixed(2)} &lt; 1</strong> (longshots overweighted, favourites underweighted).
            The new point: γ is itself invariant — <strong>no drift over 20 years</strong>
            (sd {cp.gamma_sd_season.toFixed(2)}/season, β = {cp.trend_beta >= 0 ? '+' : ''}{cp.trend_beta.toFixed(4)}/yr) and
            tightly clustered across leagues (sd {cp.gamma_sd_league.toFixed(2)}). The preference is a structural
            constant, not a process.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal">
          <img src="/f9_cpt.png" alt="Fitted Tversky–Kahneman probability weighting, and γ by season flat within the between-league band"
            style="width:100%;border-radius:12px;border:1px solid var(--line)" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider" />

  <!-- TIMELINE -->
  <section id="timeline" style="background:var(--surface-2)">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal">
        <div class="eyebrow">06 · How we got here</div>
        <h2>Fifteen phases, each verified.</h2>
        <p class="lede">From a frozen dataset to a derived law — every claim reproduced from one command and
          checked against an adversarially-verified literature review.</p>
      </div>
      <Timeline />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- REPRODUCE / CTA -->
  <section id="reproduce" class="dark">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-head reveal" style="max-width:60ch">
        <div class="eyebrow">Open by default</div>
        <h2>Read it, run it, check it.</h2>
        <p class="lede">The paper, the pipeline and the frozen dataset hash are all public. Every number on
          this page regenerates from one command.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="repro card reveal">
        <pre class="mono"><code>git clone https://github.com/cold-code-labs/skew-dynamic
cd skew-dynamic/study && ./run.sh   <span class="cmt"># venv + data + blocks 00→18</span></code></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-cta" style="margin-top:28px">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/paper">Read the paper →</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost ghost-d" href="https://github.com/cold-code-labs/skew-dynamic" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</Base>
<style>
  .ladder { margin-top: 18px; padding: 12px 14px; background: var(--surface); border: 1px dashed var(--line); border-radius: 10px; font-size: .82rem; color: var(--ink-soft); }
  .mini-stats { display: grid; gap: 18px; margin-top: 22px; }
  .mini-stats .stat-num { display: block; font-size: 1.4rem; color: var(--accent); }
  .mini-stats label { display: block; font-size: .82rem; color: var(--ink-faint); margin-top: 2px; max-width: 40ch; }
  .repro { padding: 8px 18px; overflow-x: auto; }
  .repro pre { margin: 0; }
  .repro code { color: #d8e6f5; font-size: .9rem; line-height: 1.7; }
  .repro .cmt { color: #6f87a4; }
  #reproduce .repro.card { background: #0e2342; border-color: #1d3a5f; }
</style>
